7. Confidence Score
Do not ask the LLM:
"Give me a confidence score."
LLMs are not reliable at objectively judging their own confidence.
Instead, calculate confidence using multiple signals.
For example:
Confidence Score =
    40% × Retrieval Similarity
  + 30% × Evidence Coverage
  + 20% × Answer Validation
  + 10% × Citation Quality
Example:
Retrieval Similarity      = 0.92
Evidence Coverage         = 0.90
Answer Validation         = 0.95
Citation Quality          = 1.00
Then:
Confidence =
(0.92 × 0.4)
+ (0.90 × 0.3)
+ (0.95 × 0.2)
+ (1.00 × 0.1)

= 92.7%
Display:
🟢 Confidence: 93%

Evidence Strength: High
Sources Used: 3
Pages: 14, 15, 16
Confidence Levels
90% - 100% → High confidence
70% - 89%  → Medium confidence
Below 70%  → Low confidence
For low confidence:
I found partially relevant information, but the document does not provide enough evidence to answer this reliably.
This is much better than hallucinating.
